62
0:03:55.120 --> 0:04:01.960
So now that we have some idea of the kinds of things that are involved in culture, let's

63
0:04:01.960 --> 0:04:05.120
look at cultural relativism.

64
0:04:05.120 --> 0:04:10.400
So cultural relativism is the idea that you can only understand beliefs and practices

65
0:04:10.400 --> 0:04:13.760
from within the construct of the culture itself.

66
0:04:13.760 --> 0:04:18.920
Now this is separate from moral relativism, which we're not going to talk about today.

67
0:04:18.920 --> 0:04:23.960
Cultural relativism has been used recently to make arguments for the continuation of

68
0:04:23.960 --> 0:04:28.840
human rights offenses on the grounds that are culturally based.

69
0:04:28.840 --> 0:04:35.800
In anthropology, cultural relativism is a means to get outside of your culture and understand

70
0:04:35.800 --> 0:04:36.800
another.

71
0:04:36.800 --> 0:04:40.560
So it's how do you step outside of your culture and get rid of those biases so that you can

72
0:04:40.560 --> 0:04:44.120
understand what's happening in another culture.

73
0:04:44.120 --> 0:04:48.800
But for people who are managing cross-cultural teams or multicultural teams, we can use cultural

74
0:04:48.800 --> 0:04:54.160
relativism as a prism through which we can discover miscommunication and we can discuss

75
0:04:54.160 --> 0:05:00.040
interactions between members.

76
0:05:00.040 --> 0:05:07.360
Cultural relativism was first recorded as a concept by Herodotus, who was a Greek historian

77
0:05:07.360 --> 0:05:10.160
from 484 to 425 BCE.

78
0:05:10.160 --> 0:05:14.400
He was writing about Darius the Great.

79
0:05:14.400 --> 0:05:19.640
Darius the Great was a Persian ruler from 522 to 486 BCE.

80
0:05:19.640 --> 0:05:24.480
Darius was inquiring about funerary customs in his empire, and as you can see, his empire

81
0:05:24.480 --> 0:05:26.880
was fairly vast.

82
0:05:26.880 --> 0:05:32.640
Now it turns out that in the eastern edge of his empire, the funerary custom was funerary

83
0:05:32.640 --> 0:05:34.520
cannibalism.

84
0:05:34.520 --> 0:05:37.520
And on the western edge, it was cremation.

85
0:05:37.520 --> 0:05:46.200
When those two populations were told about the custom of the other population, they both

86
0:05:46.200 --> 0:05:48.840
were dismayed and abhorred the other process.

87
0:05:48.840 --> 0:05:55.840
This is the first recorded case of this concept of cultural relativism.

88
0:05:55.840 --> 0:06:02.920
Now it was established as axiomatic in anthropology in the early 20th century by Franz Boas.

89
0:06:02.920 --> 0:06:09.600
Franz Boas was appointed professor of anthropology at Columbia University in the States in 1899.

90
0:06:09.600 --> 0:06:13.720
He is called the father of American anthropology.

91
0:06:13.720 --> 0:06:20.240
He first articulated the idea of cultural relativism in 1887, but he didn't coin the

92
0:06:20.240 --> 0:06:21.800
term.

93
0:06:21.800 --> 0:06:23.600
That fell to Alan Locke.

94
0:06:23.600 --> 0:06:29.120
Now Alan Locke is the first African-American Rhodes scholar.

95
0:06:29.120 --> 0:06:36.480
He was reviewing his book by Robert Lowey.

96
0:06:36.480 --> 0:06:41.520
And Robert Lowey was a student of Franz Boas and was writing about cultural relativism.

97
0:06:41.520 --> 0:06:45.520
He was a cultural relativist as opposed to a cultural evolutionist, which was popular

98
0:06:45.520 --> 0:06:48.440
in the Victorian era.

99
0:06:48.440 --> 0:06:54.640
And when reviewing his book, Alan Locke was talking about Robert Lowey's extreme cultural

100
0:06:54.640 --> 0:06:59.200
relativism, and that's the first time the phrase occurs in print.

101
0:06:59.200 --> 0:07:00.200
Okay.

102
0:07:00.200 --> 0:07:05.080
So why do we care about cultural relativism?

103
0:07:05.080 --> 0:07:09.400
We care about cultural relativism because the tools that anthropologists and ethnographers

104
0:07:09.400 --> 0:07:20.240
built to understand the culture we can use to find the friction points between cultures

105
0:07:20.240 --> 0:07:22.080
in our cross-cultural teams.

106
0:07:22.080 --> 0:07:28.800
And those friction points are going to lead to misunderstandings.

107
0:07:28.800 --> 0:07:33.200
Misunderstandings can lead to a cohesive breakdown within the team where people on the team think

108
0:07:33.200 --> 0:07:37.640
they're being undercut or that other people are working against them, sabotaging their

109
0:07:37.640 --> 0:07:39.720
efforts.

110
0:07:39.720 --> 0:07:42.760
It can also lead to a misunderstanding of what your work assignment is.

111
0:07:42.760 --> 0:07:45.680
What is it that we're trying to build?

112
0:07:45.680 --> 0:07:50.840
And if you get that wrong, you're apt to build the wrong tool altogether and your project

113
0:07:50.840 --> 0:08:00.320
will have high potential to fail and cause failure of the project.

114
0:08:00.320 --> 0:08:06.960
So let's look at a couple of examples of cultural relativism in action.

115
0:08:06.960 --> 0:08:07.960
Top light.

116
0:08:07.960 --> 0:08:14.720
Well, as it says here, without the exception of people with color vision deficiencies,

117
0:08:14.720 --> 0:08:16.920
everybody perceives color the same way.

118
0:08:16.920 --> 0:08:25.200
The light enters your eye, hits the cone, nerves fire, brain gets the message, color.

119
0:08:25.200 --> 0:08:29.120
Except some languages have no word for the color green.

120
0:08:29.120 --> 0:08:34.440
They instead use the color yellow or blue.

121
0:08:34.440 --> 0:08:40.640
So for those cultures that use those languages, stop light only has two colors.

122
0:08:40.640 --> 0:08:46.000
And the phrase go on green makes no sense.

123
0:08:46.000 --> 0:08:51.960
In Irish, the color of a person is the color of their hair.

124
0:08:51.960 --> 0:08:52.960
Okay?

125
0:08:52.960 --> 0:08:58.960
So Eric the red, okay, he wasn't Irish, but you get the idea.

126
0:08:58.960 --> 0:09:04.380
If you want to speak about a person of color, so a dark complected person, that person

127
0:09:04.380 --> 0:09:07.540
is blue.

128
0:09:07.540 --> 0:09:16.600
So the translation of black lives matter and blue lives matter into Irish becomes the same

129
0:09:16.600 --> 0:09:19.240
phrase.

130
0:09:19.240 --> 0:09:26.060
So a distinction that is so important and so prevalent in American US culture is lost

131
0:09:26.060 --> 0:09:31.000
in translation.

132
0:09:31.000 --> 0:09:38.200
So talk about icons, phrases, phrases and gestures are all culturally centered and that

